    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-09-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-09-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="327"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d327">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/936</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GGW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Guthrie</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Tokyo</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-09-01">
                        <hi rend="italic">September 1, 1914</hi>.</date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received September 23</hi>.] </dateline>
                <p rend="flushleft">No. 119]</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my telegram of August 15, 12
                        p.m.,<note n="1" xml:id="d327fn1">Ante, <ref target="#pg_170"
                        >170</ref>.</note> transmitting the text of Japan’s ultimatum to Germany, I
                    have the honor to enclose an English translation of the proclamation of
                        war,<note n="2" xml:id="d327fn2">Ante, <ref target="#pg_175"
                        >175</ref>.</note> which was issued at noon of the 23d ultimo, the date of
                    expiration of the multi Tatum, simultaneously with which the German Ambassador
                    was handed his passport.</p>
                <p>It was the general conviction here that Germany would not comply with the terms
                    of the ultimatum, and that war was inevitable, so that the proclamation was
                    received by the public with but little surprise.</p>
                <p>The vernacular press unanimously supported the Government in its action,
                    recognizing Japan’s obligations under the alliance with England, and her duty to
                    preserve the peace of the Far East, and to protect international shipping in
                    Oriental waters.</p>
                <p>Some of the newspapers referred to the intervention of Germany following the
                    Chino-Japanese War, and expressed satisfaction at the opportunity afforded for
                    retaliation. The efforts of the German Emperor to imbue Europe with the fear of
                    a “yellow peril” were also recalled.</p>
                <p>The promise of the Government to restore Kiaochow to China provoked some
                    discussion, and while most of the journals raised no objections, some of them
                    considered that as Germany had rejected the ultimatum, Japan was no longer bound
                    by the terms thereof, and was at liberty to retain that territory as a prize of
                    war.</p>
                <p>There are also enclosed English translations<note n="3" xml:id="d327fn3">Not
                        printed.</note> of the list of articles regarded as contraband during the
                    war between Japan and Germany, of the regulations relating to German merchantmen
                    anchored in or bound for Japanese ports at the time of the declaration of war.
                    The articles of contraband practically correspond with those provided by the
                    conference of London, with one important exception, that aircraft are
                    transferred from conditional to absolute contraband.</p>
                <p>A special session of the Diet is to be convoked on the 3d instant, to vote the
                    war budget for the current fiscal year, which it is said will amount to about
                    $18,000,000.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GGW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">George W. Guthrie</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
